## Symptoms & fixes

### `Usage UI not accessible`

| Symptom                                    | Cause                                | Fix                                                                     |
| ------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `http://127.0.0.1:4002` connection refused | Gateway not running or port conflict | Start gateway: `discursive start`; check gateway log for `usage_ui_url` |

### `Chart won't load`

| Symptom                              | Cause                                        | Fix                                                                                                                              |
| ------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Blank chart area or JS console error | Chart.js not served (offline-first — no CDN) | Chart.js is vendored in `static/chart.umd.min.js` and served at `/static/chart.umd.min.js` — verify `embed.FS` includes the file |

### `Cost estimate uses wrong price row`

| Symptom                                      | Cause                                                                    | Fix                                                                                       |
| -------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Usage $ doesn't match provider invoice shape | Priced pre-mapping alias, wrong provider table, or Cursor comparison row | Resolve alias→**provider+real model**; pick Moonshot vs DeepSeek table; never Cursor rows |

### `INFO flooded with every API call`

| Symptom                             | Cause                   | Fix                                                         |
| ----------------------------------- | ----------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- |
| One log line per completion at INFO | Per-call logged at Info | Use `LogEvent` at Debug; `usage_summary` at Info after idle |

### `Zero cache-hit tokens despite large prompt — code or upstream?`

| Symptom                                                                                                          | Cause                                                                                       | Fix                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `cache_hit_tokens=0` + `cache_miss_tokens=0` with large `prompt_tokens` makes the operator suspect a parsing bug | Upstream genuinely returned no cache data (cold request, prefix change, or provider switch) | Add a diagnostic `slog.Debug` at the single choke point (`recordUsage`) that fires when `CacheHitTokens==0 && CacheMissTokens==0 && PromptTokens>1024`. This signals "upstream reported no cache" vs silent "might be broken." The log confirms the data path is working correctly; 0 cache hits on request 1 of a new session is expected, not a bug. |

### `CSS !important silently overrides inline styles`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| Inline `style="width:160px"` on an `<img>` element has no visible effect — the image stays at its old size despite repeated edits | A CSS rule with `!important` (e.g. `.tt-logo-row img { width: 60px !important; }`) has higher specificity than inline styles. The browser silently applies the `!important` rule with zero console warnings. | Search CSS for `!important` rules matching the element / class / selector chain, then either remove the `!important` or update the CSS value to match desired outcome. Never assume inline styles take precedence when `!important` is in play anywhere in the cascade. |

### `Browser native tooltip shows raw HTML instead of rendered content`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| A `title` or `data-tip` attribute containing HTML (`<br>`, `<img>`, etc.) renders as literal text in the browser's native tooltip | Browser native tooltips (triggered by `title` attribute or similar) display attribute values as plain text — they cannot render HTML. | Do not put HTML in `title`/`data-tip` attributes. For rich tooltips (images, line-breaks, bold text), dynamically inject a positioned `<span>` or `<div>` element on hover and remove it on mouse leave. |

### `Frontend fetch to external API blocked by CORS`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| `fetch()` to an external API (e.g. `api.frankfurter.app`) from the Usage UI page fails with a CORS error in the browser console | The Usage UI page is served from `127.0.0.1:4002` by the Go embedding `net/http` server. External APIs typically do not include `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: http://127.0.0.1:4002` in their CORS headers, so the browser blocks the cross-origin request. | Add a Go backend proxy handler (e.g. `/api/exchange-rate`) that does the external HTTP call server-side and returns the data to the frontend. The proxy call is server-to-server, which is not subject to browser CORS. |

### `JS innerHTML replacement wipes static children`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| A `<select>` dropdown appears empty after JS runs, even though `<option>` tags are present in the static HTML | JavaScript code that sets `element.innerHTML = <new string>` replaces the entire content of the element. Any static `<option>` children written in the HTML are lost — they are not part of the JS-built string. | Consistently build all children in JS (not a mix of static HTML + JS innerHTML). Alternatively, use `insertAdjacentHTML` or DOM API methods that append without replacing siblings. |

### `Money symbol function undefined at page load`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| Console error `moneySymbol is not defined` during page initialization | A function is referenced in an inline JS expression (e.g. inside `innerHTML` assignment) before it is defined in the script source. JavaScript hoists function declarations but only within the same script block; `innerHTML` assignments from earlier DOM updates execute before later `<script>` tags. | Define shared utility functions (currency formatting, etc.) at the top of the `<script>` block, before any code that renders HTML using those functions. Alternatively, use template literals that evaluate at call time rather than at HTML-construction time. |

### `Period dropdown empty after HTML reorder`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| After swapping the order of two `<select>` dropdowns in the HTML, the period dropdown shows no options | The `<option>` tags for the period `<select>` were accidentally deleted or moved during the edit. The `<select>` element exists but has no children. | When reordering HTML elements, verify that each `<select>` retains its `<option>` children in the final position. Use git diff to confirm no `<option>` loss. |

### `Chart.js tooltip sizing overridden by CSS`

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
| ----- | ---- | ----- |
| Chart.js configuration sets `bodyFont.size` or similar tooltip styling, but the rendered tooltip does not respect it | Chart.js renders tooltips using Canvas or inline-styled HTML, but CSS rules targeting `.chartjs-tooltip` or the custom tooltip container may override Chart.js' internal styles. | For `external` tooltip rendering (where Chart.js calls your callback), you control the DOM entirely — set styles directly on your custom tooltip element. For built-in tooltips, use Chart.js tooltip callbacks to modify styling; avoid CSS rules that broadly target `.chartjs-tooltip *`. |

